/*
https://leetcode.com/problems/convert-binary-search-tree-to-sorted-doubly-linked-list/description/


Convert a Binary Search Tree to a sorted Circular Doubly-Linked List in place.

You can think of the left and right pointers as synonymous to the predecessor and successor pointers in a doubly-linked list. For a circular doubly linked list, the predecessor of the first element is the last element, and the successor of the last element is the first element.

We want to do the transformation in place. After the transformation, the left pointer of the tree node should point to its predecessor, and the right pointer should point to its successor. You should return the pointer to the smallest element of the linked list.

 

Example 1:



Input: root = [4,2,5,1,3]


Output: [1,2,3,4,5]

Explanation: The figure below shows the transformed BST. The solid line indicates the successor relationship, while the dashed line means the predecessor relationship.

Example 2:

Input: root = [2,1,3]
Output: [1,2,3]
 

Constraints:

The number of nodes in the tree is in the range [0, 2000].
-1000 <= Node.val <= 1000
All the values of the tree are unique.

Use an in-order traversal to visit nodes in sorted order and “stitch” them into a circular doubly-linked list on the fly.

Idea

Maintain two pointers:

first = head (smallest node seen so far)

prev = previously visited node in in-order

For each visited node cur:

Link prev.right = cur and cur.left = prev.

If prev == null, this is the first node → set first = cur.

Update prev = cur.

After traversal, close the circle:

first.left = prev and prev.right = first.

Time: O(n), Space: O(h) recursion stack (h = tree height).
(You can do Morris traversal for O(1) extra space if required.)

Visual walkthrough with an example

Consider this BST:

        4
      /   \
     2     5
    / \
   1   3

In-order order

1, 2, 3, 4, 5 (sorted)

What inorder(root) does (the stitching)

We keep two references:

first = null at start (will become 1)

prev = null at start (tracks the previous node in in-order)

We visit nodes in in-order and link prev <-> curr each time.

Step	Visit curr	Action	Resulting links	first	prev
1	1	prev is null → set first = 1	(none yet)	1	1
2	2	link prev.right = 2, 2.left = prev (1)	1 ⇄ 2	1	2
3	3	link 2.right = 3, 3.left = 2	1 ⇄ 2 ⇄ 3	1	3
4	4	link 3.right = 4, 4.left = 3	1 ⇄ 2 ⇄ 3 ⇄ 4	1	4
5	5	link 4.right = 5, 5.left = 4	1 ⇄ 2 ⇄ 3 ⇄ 4 ⇄ 5	1	5

Now we have a linear doubly-linked list (head first = 1, tail prev = 5):

1 ⇄ 2 ⇄ 3 ⇄ 4 ⇄ 5
^                 ^
|                 |
first             prev

Closing the circle (your two lines)
first.left = prev;   // 1.left = 5
prev.right = first;  // 5.right = 1


Now it’s circular:

... ⇄ 5 ⇄ 1 ⇄ 2 ⇄ 3 ⇄ 4 ⇄ 5 ⇄ 1 ⇄ ...
          ↑                       ↑
        first                   prev


The predecessor of 1 is 5.

The successor of 5 is 1.

That’s exactly the required circular doubly list.

*/

